Date: Sat, 3 May 1997 15:06:29 -0400 (EDT)
From: "Michael L. Perdue" <mperdue@asrr.arsusda.gov>
Subject: Re: PRO/AH> Ebola virus, genetic stability (04)
I agree with Brian Hjelle regarding the dual nature of evolution
(adaptation) of RNA viruses. We have recently found an H5 avian influenza
virus lineage which clearly appears to have been stably retained in
migratory waterfowl over a period of 8 years (based on HA gene sequences)
and at the same time having given rise to a branch in which the HA is
clearly evolving at a significant measurable rate (perhaps as a result of
having passed back and forth among various waterfowl species).
When these viruses enter another species such as a stationary poultry
population, the measurable mutation rate jumps significantly (or at least
that's what happend in the AI outbreak in Mexico).
---
Mike Perdue
Michael L. Perdue, Ph.D.
