[2]
Date: Sun, 4 May 97 18:25:23 -0400 (EDT)
From: Bruce Phillips <bap@med.pitt.edu>
Subject: RNA virus stability
While the engine for driving the "potential" for genetic variability is
primarily the error-proness of RNA polymerases (and reverse transcriptases
in the case of HIV), the fact is that other considerations play an equal or
more important role in whether that potential is expressed. Measles virus
exists as a single phenotype. Picornaviruses breed true as well. Yet their
polymerases/transcriptases are just as error-prone as the RT of HIV.
Therefore, one can presuppose that these other viruses generate mutants but
the infectivity of the virus is so tightly constrained, for example, the
measles virus surface proteins or the picornavirus capsid proteins do not
tolerate much change without rendering the virus non-infectious, that the
potential genetic variability is not manifested. In contrast, the gp120
protein seems to tolerate an extraordinary degree of alteration while
maintaining its function thus allowing the variants produced by the HIV
reverse transcriptase to survive AND escape antibody-mediated neutralization.
We seem so pre-focused on the polymerases that we sometimes overlook the
equally important influence of protein structure versus function.
---
Bruce Phillips
