From: MorganKlan@aol.com
Date: Sun, 4 May 1997 00:31:38 -0400 (EDT)
Subject: Re: PRO/AH> Ebola virus, genetic stability: RFI
I think you make a very good point although to be honest I'm not sure that I
know enough about the Ebola pol gene to comment personally. I have wondered
why the Ebola virus has been so adept at eluding the virus hunters attempts
at unlocking its life cycle. One of the possibilities that I have come up
with thus far is the possibility of reading frame shift. In other words, the
virus may exist in a more natural less virulent stage in nature which makes
it appear as an unlikely canidate for causing the lethal hemorrhagic disease
that it is now so famously known for. Are you familiar with any such
examples in natural systems if so would like to hear from you!!
--
Dr. Anthony Littrell
